You decide whether long-document continuity memory should be used for this
translation job.

Do not decide from document type labels alone. Do not use rules like
"fiction always needs memory" or "manual never needs memory". Decide from the
actual source sample, document context, and whether later scopes are likely to
depend on earlier scopes.

Use document length as a supporting signal, not as a standalone rule. A short
document often does not need long-document memory because local context is
enough. A long document is more likely to benefit from memory only when earlier
scopes create durable context for later scopes. A long manual with independent
sections may still be "off" or "selective"; a shorter narrative with strong
cross-scope dependencies may still be "selective".

Long-document continuity memory is useful only when earlier translated scopes
contain durable context that later scopes need, such as:
- unresolved references, promises, threats, decisions, deadlines, or open states
- relationships/dependencies among people, organizations, institutions,
  procedures, systems, concepts, or document states
- narrative/discourse progression that changes how later text should be
  interpreted
- stable register or speech-pattern information that later scopes must preserve

Long-document continuity memory is risky or low-value when:
- each section can be translated independently from local context
- the document is mostly term-definition rows, abbreviation tables, repeated
  instructions, or short standalone entries
- terminology consistency is the main need; Document Term Memory handles that
- adding earlier context is likely to contaminate short cells, glossary rows, or
  unrelated sections

Return one policy:
- "off": do not create/use continuity memory for this job
- "selective": create/update memory, but inject only selected relevant memory
  candidates into translation prompts
- "always": create/update memory and inject selected continuity memory into
  every translation prompt because earlier context is consistently important

Prefer "selective" when the document has some cross-scope dependencies but not
every later scope needs memory. Prefer "off" when local context and terminology
memory are enough. Use "always" only when continuity is central throughout.

Return compact JSON only.

<TARGET_LANGUAGE>
{{ target_lang }}
</TARGET_LANGUAGE>

<DOCUMENT_FORMAT>
{{ doc_format }}
</DOCUMENT_FORMAT>

<DOCUMENT_METRICS format="json">
{{ metrics | tojson }}
</DOCUMENT_METRICS>

<STYLE_OPTIONS format="json">
{{ style_options | tojson }}
</STYLE_OPTIONS>

<PRE_TRANSLATION_ANALYSIS format="json">
{{ pre_translation_analysis | tojson }}
</PRE_TRANSLATION_ANALYSIS>

<SOURCE_SAMPLE format="json">
{{ source_sample | tojson }}
</SOURCE_SAMPLE>

Return JSON with this shape:
{
  "memory_policy": "off | selective | always",
  "reason": "Brief context-based reason.",
  "expected_benefit": "What memory would improve, if anything.",
  "risk": "What memory could harm, if anything.",
  "selection_guidance": "If selective or always, what kind of continuity memory should be retrieved for later scopes."
}
